{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625292"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:22:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:22:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17017"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17017"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70541"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9707"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56005"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5403"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22846"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23679"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70541"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is studying birth records from a large hospital system over the past 50 years. The data excludes any pregnancies with prenatal sex determination or selective termination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the expected ratio of male to female births in this natural population?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["105 males per 100 females","110 males per 100 females","100 males per 100 females","95 males per 100 females","90 males per 100 females"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe natural human sex ratio at birth is approximately \u003Cstrong\u003E105 males per 100 females\u003C/strong\u003E. This slight male bias is a biological constant observed across different human populations when artificial selection is not present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E110 males per 100 females\u003C/strong\u003E - This ratio is higher than the natural birth ratio and would suggest artificial sex selection is occurring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E100 males per 100 females\u003C/strong\u003E - Although this equal ratio might seem logical, it does not reflect the natural male bias seen at birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E95 males per 100 females\u003C/strong\u003E - This female-biased ratio is more commonly seen in adult populations due to higher male mortality rates throughout life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E90 males per 100 females\u003C/strong\u003E - This significant female bias does not occur naturally at birth and would suggest artificial intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe male bias at birth is thought to be an evolutionary adaptation that compensates for higher male mortality rates throughout life. This ratio is remarkably consistent across different populations and time periods when artificial sex selection is not present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The human sex ratio at birth naturally favours males with approximately 105 males born for every 100 females.","This male bias at birth is a biological constant across human populations regardless of geography or ethnicity.","The excess of male births compensates for higher male mortality throughout life."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Austad SN. The human prenatal sex ratio: A major surprise. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2015 Apr 21;112(16):4839-40. doi: 10.1073/pnas.1505165112. Epub 2015 Apr 6. PMID: 25848060; PMCID: PMC4413335."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56005"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17017"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56005"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T19:12:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T19:12:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9707"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70541"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","links":{"s